post_text: Parents - Packets for your child can be picked up this week between 9AM and 12PM. Breakfast can also be picked up from 9am-12pm and Lunch can be picked up from 11pm-12pm. Please do pick ups at the back door near the cafeteria entrance near Winton Road. If you pull up, a staff member will come out and assist you. At this time, no one is permitted in the building as we are doing a deep cleaning to assure the safety of students and staff. Food will be provided this week but not during the week of our original spring break. We will give you more info later as we get closer to the end of spring break. We WILL get through this together! Take care and stay healthy!

post_text:
Wildcat Families:

Reading is one of the most important skills that you can teach a child. Of the skills children learn, it is the one you can influence the most. Giving kids access to good books and the opportunity to choose books will motivate them to read more. And like most acquired skills, the more kids practice reading, the better they'll get.

We invite you to visit our Scholastic Book Fair and experience a celebration of reading that provides families the opportunity to get involved in a universal mission: encouraging kids to read everyday os they can lead better lives.

Reading is vital to every child's success and raising kids as readers means getting involved while they're young. Now is the time. Since there will never be a substitute for a parent's direct involvement in his/her child's education, please make plans to visit our Book Fair.

Book Fair Dates: Monday, April 9th - Friday, April 13th

Shopping Hours: 9:30 am _ 2:30 pm

We look forward to having you participate in our Fair, and remember, all purchases benefit our school.

post_text:
Scholars & Leaders Personal Library Club Visit the William Howard Taft House

On March 2, 2018, thirty-five participants in the Scholars & Leaders Personal Library Club visited the William Howard Taft National Historical Site in Mount Auburn. Ms. Richard, Lead Intervention Specialist, is the Founder and Sponsor of the Scholars & Leaders Personal Library Club. The goal of this 2nd field trip was to provide students with an opportunity to explore their hometown, learn more about Cincinnatian William Howard Taft, who became the 27th President of the United States, and find out more about Ohio history. In the Education Center, students watched a video and viewed displays about the life of William Howard Taft. Park Rangers provided a guided tour of William Howard Taft's childhood home. Fourth graders were offered the opportunity to earn a free "Every Kid in a Park Pass". This pass will allow the students and their families free entry into thousands of federal sites in the United States.

post_text:
Winton Preparatory Academy is Celebrating Black History

“You must give your own story to the world.”---Carter G. Woodson

Students throughout Winton Preparatory Academy are celebrating Black History. Middle School students participated in research projects requiring them to write essays, poems, make art, and create display boards representing a variety of African-Americans in various fields. These projects were assigned by Ms. Ottariano the English Language Arts teacher and Mrs. McCoy the Social Studies teacher.

Students in Ms. Indra Brown’s third-grade class are enthusiastic about the various facts they have learned.

“Black people and white people drank from different water fountains.”

“George Washington Carver discovered many ways to use the peanut.”

“Many people died so we could get an education.”



Mrs. McLean read stories, taught lessons, and required her first-grade class to do assignments and memorize facts about Black History.
